@page "/about/why-nbt"

<PageTitle>Why Write the NBT?</PageTitle>

<link rel="stylesheet" href="Pages/ContentPage.css" />

<div class="content-page">
    <FluentBreadcrumb>
        <FluentBreadcrumbItem Href="/">Home</FluentBreadcrumbItem>
        <FluentBreadcrumbItem Href="/about/why-nbt">Why NBT?</FluentBreadcrumbItem>
    </FluentBreadcrumb>

    <h1>Why Write the NBT?</h1>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Understanding the Purpose</h2>
        <p>
            The National Benchmark Tests (NBTs) provide valuable information about your academic readiness for 
            university-level study. They complement your school results by assessing skills that are essential 
            for success in tertiary education.
        </p>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Key Benefits</h2>
        
        <div class="benefit-item">
            <FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size24.BuildingMultiple())" Color="Color.Accent" />
            <div>
                <h3>University Admissions</h3>
                <p>
                    Many South African universities require or recommend NBT results as part of their admission process. 
                    NBT scores are used alongside your matric results to make informed admission decisions.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="benefit-item">
            <FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size24.PersonFeedback())" Color="Color.Accent" />
            <div>
                <h3>Identify Your Strengths</h3>
                <p>
                    NBT results help you understand your academic strengths and areas that may need development. 
                    This self-awareness can guide your study choices and preparation for university.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="benefit-item">
            <FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size24.PeopleCommunity())" Color="Color.Accent" />
            <div>
                <h3>Access Support Services</h3>
                <p>
                    Universities use NBT results to identify students who may benefit from additional academic support, 
                    tutoring, or foundation programs to enhance their success.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="benefit-item">
            <FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size24.BookSearch())" Color="Color.Accent" />
            <div>
                <h3>Appropriate Course Placement</h3>
                <p>
                    NBT scores help universities place you in courses that match your current competency level, 
                    ensuring you're neither under-challenged nor overwhelmed.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="benefit-item">
            <FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size24.Certificate())" Color="Color.Accent" />
            <div>
                <h3>Inform Career Choices</h3>
                <p>
                    Understanding your performance in Academic Literacy, Quantitative Literacy, and Mathematics can 
                    help you make informed decisions about study fields and career paths.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>How Universities Use NBT Results</h2>
        <p>Different universities use NBT results in various ways:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Admission Requirements:</strong> Some programs require minimum NBT performance levels</li>
            <li><strong>Placement Tests:</strong> Determining readiness for specific courses or programs</li>
            <li><strong>Support Planning:</strong> Identifying students for academic development programs</li>
            <li><strong>Scholarship Decisions:</strong> Some institutions consider NBT results for funding allocations</li>
            <li><strong>Extended Programs:</strong> Recommending foundation or extended degree programs when appropriate</li>
        </ul>
        <FluentMessageBar Intent="MessageIntent.Info" Style="margin-top: 1rem;">
            Always check with your chosen university/universities to understand their specific NBT requirements 
            and how they use the results.
        </FluentMessageBar>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>NBTs vs. Matric Results</h2>
        <p>NBTs are not a replacement for your matric results. Instead, they:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Provide an <strong>independent assessment</strong> of academic readiness</li>
            <li>Measure <strong>transferable skills</strong> rather than curriculum content</li>
            <li>Offer <strong>comparative data</strong> across all South African students</li>
            <li>Help universities make <strong>more informed decisions</strong> about admissions and support</li>
        </ul>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>When Should You Write?</h2>
        <p>
            It's recommended to write the NBTs in your <strong>final year of high school (Grade 12)</strong> or earlier. 
            This allows you to:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Include NBT results in your university applications</li>
            <li>Retake the test if needed (up to 2 tests per year)</li>
            <li>Plan for additional preparation or support if required</li>
            <li>Avoid last-minute stress and venue availability issues</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Remember: Bookings open from <strong>April 1st</strong> each year, and results are valid for 
            <strong>3 years</strong> from the date of booking.
        </p>
    </FluentCard>

    <div class="action-section">
        <FluentButton Appearance="Appearance.Accent" 
                    IconStart="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.PersonAdd())"
                    OnClick="@(() => Navigation.NavigateTo("/register"))">
            Register Now
        </FluentButton>
        <FluentButton Appearance="Appearance.Outline"
                    IconStart="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.Info())"
                    OnClick="@(() => Navigation.NavigateTo("/about/tests"))">
            Learn About the Tests
        </FluentButton>
    </div>
</div>

<style>
    .benefit-item {
        display: flex;
        align-items: flex-start;
        gap: 1rem;
        margin: 1.5rem 0;
        padding: 1rem;
        background: var(--neutral-layer-2);
        border-radius: 4px;
    }

    .benefit-item h3 {
        margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;
        color: var(--accent-fill-rest);
    }

    .benefit-item p {
        margin: 0;
    }
</style>

@code {
    [Inject] private NavigationManager Navigation { get; set; } = default!;
}
